{{infobox religious building | name = Yugasan Rendaiji | native_name = {{ill|Rendaiji|ja|蓮台寺|12=draft|12=draft}} | religious_affiliation = {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft|12=draft}} | image = [[File:{{ill|Rendaiji Main Hall|ja|蓮台寺 01|12=draft|12=draft}}.jpg|270px]] | image description = Main Hall (Sōhonden) | address = {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Kurashiki City|ja|倉敷市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kojima Yuka 2855 | latitude = 34 | latitude minutes = 30 | latitude seconds = 20.25 | longitude = 133 | longitude minutes = 51 | longitude seconds = 2.5 | mountain_name = {{ill|Yuka-yama|ja|由加山|12=draft|12=draft}} | sect = {{ill|Shingon Buddhism, Mimuro-ha|ja|真言宗御室派|12=draft|12=draft}} | temple_ranking = Classified as an “Extraordinary Head Temple” | main_image = {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|lt=Eleven-faced Kannon Bosatsu|ja|十一面観音菩薩|12=draft|12=draft}}{{ill|Yogācāra Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|12=draft|12=draft}} | founded = Tradition: Year 3 of {{ill|Daibō Era|ja|大宝|12=draft|12=draft}} (703) | founder = | official_name = Yuka-yama Yogācāra Daigongen Rendaiji | alternate_names = | pilgrimage = {{ill|China 33 Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|中国三十三観音霊場|12=draft|12=draft}} No. 6{{ill|Hyakuhachi Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|百八観音霊場|12=draft|12=draft}} No. 8 | cultural_properties = Guest Hall, Tahō Tower, Kikujidō Illustrated Folding Screen, and the Bell (Designated as a Prefectural Important Cultural Property)Copper Sword (Designated as a City Important Cultural Property) | map2 = {{Infobox mapframe|zoom=11|marker=religious-buddhist|frame-width=240|frame-latitude=34.5|frame-longitude=133.88}}{{Location map|Japan Okayama|mark=Japanese Map symbol (Temple).svg|marksize=12|label=Rendaiji|float=center}} }} '''Yugasan Rendaiji''' ({{ill|Rendaiji|ja|蓮台寺|12=draft|12=draft}}) is a temple of the {{ill|Shingon Mimuro Sect|ja|真言宗御室派|12=draft|12=draft}} located in the Kojima area of {{ill|Kurashiki City|ja|倉敷市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is classified as an Extraordinary Head Temple. Its mountain name is Yuka-yama (由加山), and its principal images are the Eleven-faced Kannon Bosatsu and Yogācāra Daigongen. It is pilgrimage site No. 6 on the {{ill|China 33 Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|中国三十三観音霊場|12=draft|12=draft}} and No. 8 on the {{ill|Hyakuhachi Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|百八観音霊場|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History == Tradition holds that in the 10th year of the {{ill|Tenpyō Era|ja|天平|12=draft|12=draft}} (738), the monk {{ill|Gyōki|ja|行基|12=draft|12=draft}} enshrined the Eleven-faced Kannon Bosatsu (the principal image) along with Yogācāra Daigongen (a manifestation of the trace of Amida and Yakushi) and thus founded the temple. Although the temple declined after being damaged by warfare at the end of the Heian period, it was revived during the Muromachi period by a high-ranking monk. In the Edo period it received the protection of the {{ill|Okayama Han|ja|岡山藩|12=draft|12=draft}} of Bizen Province. Long revered for its Yogācāra Daigongen, following the Meiji [[Shinbutsu Bunri]] edict, a separate shrine – later known as {{ill|Yuka Shrine|ja|由加神社本宮|12=draft|12=draft}} – was established within the temple grounds.
After the post–World War II dissolution of State Shinto, although formally separated, the monastic staff continued to perform rituals in the main hall so that, in practice, the pre–Meiji state of affairs was restored. As a result, while Yuka Shrine retained its legal status as a separate religious corporation and maintained its own priests, it was in effect nearly dormant.
In 1997 (Heisei 9) on March 3, Yuka Shrine began independent religious activities by occupying part of the temple buildings. Since then Rendaiji and Yuka Shrine have been in conflict—with Rendaiji seeking the return of its buildings—though Yuka Shrine continues its independent operations.
A traditional custom called “Ryōmairi” (simultaneous pilgrimage to both shrines) developed in the Edo period in which pilgrims visited both the Yogācāra Daigongen of Yugasan and the {{ill|Kinpirō Daigongen|ja|金毘羅大権現|12=draft|12=draft}} (now at {{ill|Kintōhira-gū|ja|金刀比羅宮|12=draft|12=draft}}) in Sanuki Province.
== Overview == It is widely venerated as a protective deity against misfortune. In 2007 (Heisei 19) a 7.59‑meter tall wooden statue of the immovable 【ill|Fudō Myōō|ja|不動明王】—the tallest of its kind in Japan—was completed.
The approach (sando) up Yuka-yama is lined by a traditional town (monzenchō) whose local specialty is the sweet rice cake known as {{ill|Ankoro Mochi|ja|あんころ餅|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Cultural Properties == ; Okayama Prefecture–designated Important Cultural Properties * The Nakazato Fujizuka (mound) – one of the fujizuka built by the Fuji-kō group (pilgrims to Mt. Fuji) from the Edo period to early Showa period. In Kurashiki it is one of the larger mounds, with a height of 12 meters from its southern base and a diameter of 30 meters. A stone monument dated to 1822 (Bunsei 5) indicates that its construction began in the Edo period. Among 36 stone structures, its dōsojin monument is unique in the district.
; Treasures * Ema (votive plaques) depicting the subjugation of the Yamata no Orochi (dating from Tenpō 5, July) * Ema commemorating a Fuji ascent (dating from Keien 7, June) * Ema depicting a pilgrimage to Ise (by Fujigoro and Murata Masatarō, dating from Keien 3, March)＜ref＞{{Cite book|和書|author=Ishikamin Library Local Materials Section|title=Ema of Nerima|publisher=Nerima City Board of Education|year=1978|page=175,178}}＜/ref＞
== Address == * 2855 Kojima Yuka, Kurashiki City, Okayama Prefecture
== Access == * By car: From the {{ill|Setchu Chūō Expressway|ja|瀬戸中央自動車道|12=draft|12=draft}} at {{ill|Mizushima IC|ja|水島IC|12=draft|12=draft}}, take {{ill|Okayama Kojima Road No.21|ja|岡山児島線|12=draft|12=draft}} east toward Okayama, and at the “Gōnai” intersection turn east onto {{ill|Okayama Tamano Fukuda Line|ja|玉野福田線|12=draft|12=draft}}. Continue straight along the route – about 15 minutes by car. * By train: Approximately a 15‑minute taxi ride from {{ill|Kojima Station|ja|児島駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Seto Ohashi Line|ja|瀬戸大橋線|12=draft|12=draft}}. * By bus: A “Shimoden” bus (downward bus) runs from Kojima Station; however, there are only two round-trips per day (one in the morning, one in the evening) with a stop time of about 5 minutes. (Buses do not run on Saturdays, Sundays, holidays, or the New Year’s three days.)
== Adjacent Sacred Sites == ; {{ill|China 33 Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|中国三十三観音霊場|12=draft|12=draft}} : 5 {{ill|Hōkai-in|ja|法界院|12=draft|12=draft}} – '''6 Yugasan Rendaiji''' – 7 {{ill|Entsū-ji|ja|円通寺|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Bibliography == * {{Cite book|和書|author=Kurashiki High School Educational Research Group, Social Studies Division, History Section|title=New Edition: Historical Strolls of Okayama Prefecture|publisher=Yamakawa Shuppan|year=1991|pages=96–97}} * Local explanatory plaques
== References ==
{{Reflist|group=2}}
== See Also == * {{ill|Yuka Shrine Main|ja|由加神社本宮|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Kumano Shrine (Kurashiki)|ja|熊野神社 (倉敷市林)|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Yoshida Yoshi-dō|ja|柴田義董|12=draft|12=draft}} – credited with painting the 50‐faced barrier paintings at Rendaiji.
== External Links == * {{Commonscat|Rendaiji}} * [https://yugasan.jp/ Yugasan Rendaiji Official Website] * [https://www.city.kurashiki.okayama.jp/bunkahogo/ Kurashiki City Cultural Properties Protection Division]
